The paper deals with lower bounds for dynamic data structures, which is a topic in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of online communication complexity is a central theme in the paper, which suggests that it could also be classified under cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also involves some combinatorial arguments and probabilistic analysis, which are relevant to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents some experimental results, which could potentially fall under the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
